    "Step 0: Idle",
    "Step 1: Thinking\n  [{ Id = 61a46427-63c4-463b-a43e-02acac146370\n     CorrelationId = CorrelationId 3b1ce983-9b41-4111-9029-39a8c51107bf\n     Sender = System\n     Receiver = Some (Agent (AgentId 74d70792-55e0-4374-9350-2c6e6bcd6ddc))\n     Performative = Request\n     Intent = Some Coding\n     Constraints = { MaxTokens = None\n                     MaxComplexity = None\n                     Timeout = None\n                     KnowledgeBoundary = [] }\n     Ontology = None\n     Language = \u0022text\u0022\n     Content =\n      \u0022To calculate the factorial of a number using recursion in F#, I\u0027ll follow these steps:\n\n1. Define a recursive function \u0060factorial\u0060 that takes an integer as input.\n2. Handle edge cases for 0 and negative numbers.\n3. Implement the base case for the recursion (factorial of 0 is 1).\n4. Implement the recursive case to multiply the number by the factorial of the number minus one.\n\nHere\u0027s the F# code to achieve this:\n\n\u0060\u0060\u0060fsharp\n// Define a function to calculate the factorial using recursion\nlet rec factorial n =\n    // Handle edge cases for negative numbers\n    if n \u003C 0 then\n        failwith \u0022Factorial is not defined for negative numbers\u0022\n    // Base case: factorial of 0 is 1\n    elif n = 0 then\n        1\n    // Recursive case: n * factorial (n - 1)\n    else\n        n * factorial (n - 1)\n\n// Example usage:\nlet result = factorial 5\nprintfn \u0022Factorial of 5 is %d\u0022 result\n\u0060\u0060\u0060\n\nThis function will correctly calculate the factorial for non-negative integers and handle negative inputs by raising an error.\u0022\n     Timestamp = 2025-12-28 6:03:05 PM\n     Metadata = map [] }]",
